﻿# Constrained Attention Is What You Need

*A tribute to "Attention Is All You Need" -- and an argument for what comes next.*

---

## The Audit Question

I spent 20 years as an accountant. Four and a half months ago, I started building an AI coding system. I am not sure I qualify as an engineer -- but I know something about systems that are designed to catch failure.

In accounting, there is a principle so fundamental it is invisible to most people: you never let a single person authorize, execute, and verify their own work. Not because people are dishonest -- but because they are fallible. Segregation of duties, reconciliation, independent audit. The system is designed around the assumption that any individual step can go wrong.

When I started working with AI coding agents, I saw something that would get you fired in any accounting firm: the model writes the code, evaluates its own output, decides if it is done, and moves on. One actor, no separation, no independent verification. If it makes a mistake, it reviews its own mistake with the same context that produced it.

We would never accept this from a human. Why do we accept it from a machine that is, by design, probabilistic?

In every other system, we design for failure. In AI, we design for hope.

