## The Era of Expanding Attention

In 2017, Vaswani et al. published "Attention Is All You Need." It was one of the most important papers in the history of computing. The transformer architecture proved that attention mechanisms -- the ability to focus on relevant parts of input -- mattered more than depth, more than recurrence, more than raw parameter count.

The industry heard that message and ran with it. But it ran in one direction: expansion.

Bigger context windows. Longer conversations. More tokens per turn. The assumption was that if attention is what you need, then *more* attention must be better. Give the model everything, let it figure out what matters.

This led to agentic loops: systems where the model reads files, writes code, checks results, reads more files, adjusts its plan, loops until done. The context grows with every turn. The model carries the full weight of its own history -- including its mistakes, its abandoned approaches, its accumulated confusion.

We observed the cost of this expansion directly. On a benchmark task, an agentic loop solved the problem, then "optimized" it, broke it, reverted, broke it again -- burning 35,000 tokens in a self-destructive spiral. On a multi-file task, another agent looped for 10 minutes, consuming nearly 2 million tokens before we killed it. It never converged.

These are not edge cases. They are the predictable consequence of unbounded attention.

