## Constrained Attention

The insight that changed my approach was simple: current LLMs have enough capability for most tasks. Even models that are not the most advanced -- like DeepSeek-chat -- can solve complex problems. What they lack is not intelligence. What they lack is constraint.

Constraint that directs their attention. Constraint that structures how they think through a problem. Constraint that prevents them from wandering, from second-guessing, from accumulating noise.

When you constrain a model's attention -- give it only what it needs for the current step, nothing more -- something remarkable happens. It stops brute-forcing through trial and error. It starts thinking methodically. Not because you made it smarter, but because you removed the distractions that made it worse.

The evidence:

| | Constrained (red-exec) | Unconstrained (agentic loop) | Ratio |
|---|---|---|---|
| Pass rate (49 exercises) | 49/49 (100%) | 49/49 (100%) | Equal |
| Total tokens | 689K | 10,287K | **14.9x fewer** |
| Wall time | 77 min | 86 min | 1.12x faster |

Same model. Same tasks. Same pass rate. 14.9x fewer tokens. The only difference is architecture.

On multi-file tasks -- where coordination between files is required -- the gap widens further.

We publish a reproducible benchmark suite so anyone can verify these numbers:

| Task | Constrained (red-exec) | Claude Code (Sonnet) | Ratio |
|---|---|---|---|
| Module split (20 checks) | 3.9K | 90K | **23x** |
| Pipeline skeleton (11 checks) | 6.5K | 191K | **29x** |
| Tool migration (13 checks) | 10.3K | 163K | **16x** |
| **Total** | **21K** | **444K** | **21x** |

Both systems achieved 100% pass rates. red-exec costs $0.003 per run; Claude Code costs $0.77 -- a 250x cost difference. Run it yourself: `node bin/red-exec.js --benchmark multifile`.

On our internal production codebase -- a 937-line pipeline split, a 7-file tool migration, an xState skeleton with real architectural context -- the same task patterns show 12-49x cost ratios because larger codebases amplify context accumulation in agentic loops while the structured pipeline stays flat:

| Task | Constrained | Claude Code (Sonnet) | Ratio |
|---|---|---|---|
| Pipeline split (937 lines) | 10.4K | 473K | **45x** |
| Tool migration (7 files) | 44K | 547K | **12x** |
| Pipeline skeleton | 16.2K | 787K | **49x** |

The public benchmarks are the verifiable floor. Real codebases make it wider, not narrower.

But cost is only half the story. The other half is variance.

We ran the same tasks multiple times through each system. The constrained system decomposed the task the same way every time -- same files, same structure, same approach. Token variance across runs: **5.5% of mean**. The agentic loop took a different strategy every run. One run used 2 patches; the next used 10 patches, 8 file writes, and 8 search calls on the same task. Same model, same prompt, completely different execution path. Per-exercise token variance: **59% of mean**.

This is the difference between a system that *knows* how to approach a task and one that *discovers* its approach at runtime. Discovery is expensive, unpredictable, and non-repeatable. Structure is cheap, consistent, and auditable.

This is not a prompt trick. This is architecture.

