## A Compiler of Human Intent

The best analogy for what we built is a compiler.

A compiler does not explore. It does not iterate. It does not "try things and see what works." It takes high-level intent (source code) and lowers it through structured phases into executable output. Each phase has a defined input, a defined output, and a bounded scope. The phases compose deterministically.

An agentic loop is an interpreter. It processes one line at a time, maintains a running state, and the outcome depends on the entire history of execution. Interpreters are flexible, but they are unpredictable and expensive.

We built a compiler. The human declares intent -- "refactor this module into three files" -- and the system lowers that intent through structured phases into working code. Each phase receives only the context it needs from the previous phase. No phase can see the full history. No phase can decide to go back and try something different.

This is why the cost is predictable. This is why the output is consistent. This is why a smaller model, constrained by the right architecture, outperforms a larger model given unlimited freedom.

The compiler does not need the model to be brilliant. It needs the model to be focused.

