## The Human as Architect, Not Operator

There is a second meaning to "Constrained Attention" that goes beyond the machine.

Today, developers who use AI coding tools spend their time babysitting the model. They watch it write code, correct its mistakes, re-prompt when it wanders, verify its output line by line. The human's attention is consumed by the mechanics of execution.

This is backwards. The human's attention should be constrained to what only humans can do: defining intent and verifying invariants. Not "did the model write the correct syntax?" but "does this code do what I asked for, and does it meet my constraints?"

The future workflow is what I do every day with my own system: I state what I want. I define what must be true when it is done. I do not tell it how to write the code. I do not check its work line by line. I check whether the outcome satisfies my invariants.

The model handles execution. The human handles intent and governance.

This is not abdication -- it is the same principle that makes organizations work. A CFO does not write the accounting entries. They define the strategy and ensure the controls are in place. The system earns trust through process -- bounded execution, structural checks, traceability -- not through "vibes."

